    "revise": "You are the FIGURE REVISER (Opus) for \"The LLM Stack\". Chapter: content/03-pretraining/09-optimizers.md\nThe chapter's core intuitions: Adam's per-coordinate scale invariance: the ratio m_hat/sqrt(v_hat) rescales every coordinate to a near-unit step regardless of the gradient's absolute magnitude, which is why one global learning rate works on transformers' wildly heterogeneous gradients while SGD zig-zags.; The optimizer-state memory tax: AdamW stores two extra fp32 tensors (m, v) plus an fp32 master copy = 12 bytes/param, 3x the bf16 weights (16 bytes/param total). For a 7B model that is ~84 GB of optimizer state alone, dwarfing the 14 GB of weights and motivating the entire second half of the chapter.; The modern optimizers form a spectrum of how aggressively they discard the magnitude of the update while keeping its direction: Adam soft-normalizes each coordinate (~unit), Lion takes the exact per-coordinate sign (+/-1), Muon orthogonalizes a whole matrix so every singular value becomes 1. Lion is the scalar analogue, Muon the matrix analogue of the same idea.; Memory-frugal optimizers cut the '2 buffers per param' cost by different tricks: Adafactor factors the second-moment matrix into a row vector times a column vector (O(n+m) instead of O(nm)); Lion and Muon drop the second moment entirely (1 buffer).\n\nReview each of these figures (the ones this chapter just drew/edited):\n  opt-adam-scale-invariance, opt-memory-tax, opt-discard-magnitude-family, opt-muon-newton-schulz\n\nFor EACH: render and SEE it \u2014 `python3 scripts/preview_fig.py <NAME> --theme both` from /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook,\nthen view /tmp/figpreview/<NAME>.light.png and .dark.png. Judge strictly:\n  - Does it actually BUILD INTUITION for its concept (not just decorate)? Is it correct vs the chapter?\n  - Theme-safe (no hardcoded primary color; readable in BOTH light and dark)?\n  - Nothing clipped by the viewBox; no illegible overlaps; no tofu glyphs (ASCII only in the SVG)?\n  - Marker present in the chapter exactly once; figcaption has a bold lead + takeaway?\nIf a figure has ANY problem, FIX it: Edit /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook/figures/<NAME>.html (and re-render to confirm), or\nfix a missing/duplicate marker in the chapter. Re-verify after fixing.\n\nSet verdict per figure: good / fixed / still-broken / missing. `passed` = every figure good-or-fixed\nAND present. Return the structured object."
